                                <div class="document-header">
                                    <div class="document-title">üìù Problem Definition Framework</div>
                                    <span class="edit-badge">Click to edit in VS Code</span>
                                </div>
                                <div class="document-content">PROBLEM DEFINITION: GROUPTHINK IN ORGANIZATIONAL DECISION-MAKING

X ‚Üí Y Framework

Current State (X):
Our organization faces recurring groupthink within management and project teams, particularly during strategic and operational decision-making meetings. Teams often prioritize consensus over the quality of analysis, and members hesitate to challenge dominant opinions due to fear of social friction or negative evaluations. This results in decisions that lack critical evaluation, overlook potential risks, and fail to incorporate innovative ideas. Over time, this conformity has led to repetitive project outcomes, limited innovation, and avoidable strategic missteps that could have been mitigated by diverse thinking and open dissent.

Desired State (Y):
The organization aspires to establish a decision-making culture that values psychological safety, critical inquiry, and evidence-based debate. In this desired state, diverse perspectives are actively encouraged, dissent is framed as constructive, and data-driven reasoning guides conclusions. Leaders model openness to feedback, and team structures intentionally include cognitive and functional diversity. As a result, decisions will be higher in quality, innovation will increase, and risks will be better anticipated and managed.

PICOC Framework

Population (P):
Management teams and cross-functional project groups in mid- to large-sized organizations, typically composed of 5‚Äì12 members. These individuals are responsible for strategic and operational decisions that directly affect organizational performance, innovation, and risk management.

Intervention (I):
Implement structured, evidence-based interventions that reduce groupthink, including:
- Rotating devil's advocate roles during decision sessions
- Anonymous digital feedback tools to surface dissenting opinions
- Formal training on cognitive biases and critical thinking
- Team composition policies ensuring diversity in function and background
- Use of decision quality checklists and pre-mortem analysis techniques

Comparison (C):
Compared to current unstructured decision-making practices that favor harmony and speed over thorough evaluation, the new approach emphasizes open dialogue, psychological safety, and procedural fairness.

Outcome (O):
Expected measurable outcomes include:
- 25% improvement in decision quality scores (measured via post-decision review surveys)
- 20% increase in innovation proposals submitted by teams
- Reduction in strategic project rework by 15%
- Higher employee engagement and satisfaction with decision processes

Context (C):
This framework applies to knowledge-based organizational settings (e.g., corporate, technology, or professional services sectors) where complex decisions require input from diverse stakeholders. The recommended interventions can be implemented and evaluated over a 6‚Äì12 month period.

Clear Problem Statement
Our organization's current culture of consensus-driven decision-making leads to reduced innovation, poor risk assessment, and diminished decision quality. By implementing evidence-based interventions that promote constructive dissent, diversity of thought, and psychological safety, we can transition from a groupthink-prone environment to one characterized by critical thinking, creativity, and higher-quality strategic outcomes.</div>
                            </div>

                            <!-- Stakeholder Analysis Document -->
                            <div class="document-card" onclick="openContentFile('ask-stakeholder-analysis.txt')">
                                <div class="document-header">
                                    <div class="document-title">üë• Stakeholder Analysis</div>
