                            <!-- Study #1: Frazier et al. -->
                            <div class="document-card">
                                <div class="document-header">
                                    <div class="document-title">üî¨ Meta-Analysis: Frazier et al. (2017)</div>
                                    <span class="edit-badge">N=26,471 | r=0.44 | Personnel Psychology</span>
                                </div>
                                <div class="document-content">CITATION: Frazier, M. L., Fainshmidt, S., Klinger, R. L., Pezeshkan, A., & Vracheva, V. (2017). Psychological safety: A meta-analytic review and extension. Personnel Psychology, 70(1), 113-165.

META-ANALYSIS SCOPE: 136 independent studies, N=26,471 participants across industries

KEY FINDINGS:
‚Ä¢ Psychological safety ‚Üí Team performance: r = 0.44, p < .001 (19% variance explained)
‚Ä¢ Psychological safety ‚Üí Information sharing: r = 0.49
‚Ä¢ Psychological safety ‚Üí Learning behavior: r = 0.43
‚Ä¢ Effects consistent across organizational contexts, industries, and team types

METHODOLOGICAL STRENGTH:
‚úì Systematic search across 4 databases (400+ studies screened)
‚úì Random-effects model accounting for study heterogeneity
‚úì Narrow confidence intervals [0.40, 0.48]
‚úì Publication bias analysis conducted

RELEVANCE TO HYPOTHESIS:
Directly validates X‚ÜíY relationship: Low psychological safety environments exhibit suppressed information sharing and reduced team performance. Engineering teams represented in aggregated sample. Medium-to-large effect size indicates practical significance for organizational intervention.

QUALITY RATING: ‚≠ê‚≠ê‚≠ê‚≠ê‚≠ê (Excellent - Gold standard meta-analysis)</div>
                            </div>

                            <!-- CAT MANAGER ANALYSIS #1 -->
                            <div class="document-card">
                                <div class="document-header">
                                    <div class="document-title">‚úÖ Quality Appraisal: Frazier Meta-Analysis</div>
                                    <span class="edit-badge">Trustworthiness Assessment</span>
                                </div>
                                <div class="document-content">CRITICAL APPRAISAL SUMMARY

STUDY DESIGN: ‚≠ê‚≠ê‚≠ê‚≠ê‚≠ê (Excellent)
Meta-analysis represents highest level of evidence hierarchy. Systematic inclusion criteria, transparent screening process, rigorous aggregation methodology.

SAMPLE SIZE: ‚≠ê‚≠ê‚≠ê‚≠ê‚≠ê (Excellent)
Aggregated N=26,471 provides exceptional statistical power. Narrow confidence intervals indicate reliable effect size estimates.

EFFECT MAGNITUDE: ‚≠ê‚≠ê‚≠ê‚≠ê‚òÜ (Strong)
r=0.44 represents medium-to-large effect by Cohen's standards. 19% variance explained is practically significant for organizational outcomes.

BIAS CONTROL: ‚≠ê‚≠ê‚≠ê‚≠ê‚òÜ (Strong)
Funnel plot analysis, inclusion of unpublished studies, fail-safe N calculations conducted. Minor publication bias possible but unlikely to reverse findings.

GENERALIZABILITY: ‚≠ê‚≠ê‚≠ê‚≠ê‚≠ê (Excellent)
Cross-industry, multi-national sample. Effects consistent across contexts. Directly applicable to engineering/technical teams.

OVERALL CONFIDENCE: 90% (Very High)

DECISION: ‚úÖ ADOPT THIS EVIDENCE
Strengths substantially outweigh limitations. Provides strongest available scientific foundation for psychological safety ‚Üí performance relationship.</div>
                            </div>

                            <!-- Study #2: Detert & Burris -->
                            <div class="document-card">
                                <div class="document-header">
                                    <div class="document-title">üî¨ Longitudinal Study: Detert & Burris (2007)</div>
                                    <span class="edit-badge">Voice ‚Üí Decision Quality | Academy of Management Journal</span>
                                </div>
                                <div class="document-content">CITATION: Detert, J. R., & Burris, E. R. (2007). Leadership behavior and employee voice: Is the door really open? Academy of Management Journal, 50(4), 869-884.

STUDY DESIGN: Multi-wave longitudinal field study with multi-source data

KEY FINDINGS:
‚Ä¢ Employee voice behavior ‚Üí Decision quality (significant positive relationship)
‚Ä¢ Leader openness moderates the voice-performance link
‚Ä¢ Temporal separation between measures reduces common method bias
‚Ä¢ Multi-level analysis (employees nested within organizational units)

METHODOLOGICAL STRENGTH:
‚úì Longitudinal design strengthens causal inference
‚úì Multi-source data (employee reports + manager ratings)
‚úì Rare direct measurement of "decision quality" as outcome
‚úì Objective unit-level metrics supplement subjective ratings

RELEVANCE TO HYPOTHESIS:
Validates mechanism (M): Voice/dissent behavior directly improves decision quality. Demonstrates that psychological safety enables voice, which translates to measurable performance outcomes. Leader behavior identified as critical moderator.

QUALITY RATING: ‚≠ê‚≠ê‚≠ê‚≠ê‚≠ê (Excellent - Premier journal, rigorous design)</div>
                            </div>

