                                </div>
                                <div class="document-content">SOURCE: Google re:Work | Project Aristotle Internal Research

RESEARCH SCOPE: 180 engineering teams studied longitudinally over 2 years

KEY FINDING: Psychological safety emerged as the #1 predictor of team effectiveness among 5 factors studied (reliability, structure/clarity, meaning, impact, psychological safety).

OUTCOMES OBSERVED:
‚Ä¢ High-safety teams: Superior error reporting, increased innovation output, higher performance ratings
‚Ä¢ Low-safety teams: Suppressed dissent, conformity bias, reduced risk identification
‚Ä¢ Effect transcended individual talent composition

VALIDATED INTERVENTIONS:
‚úì Leader modeling of vulnerability
‚úì Structured feedback mechanisms
‚úì Explicit norms legitimizing disagreement
‚úì Team rituals normalizing risk-taking

IMPLEMENTATION INSIGHTS:
Cultural transformation requires sustained effort (quarters, not weeks). Manager training critical. Interventions must be formalized into processes, not personality-dependent.

CREDIBILITY: High (Rigorous internal research, transparent methodology, independent validation)</div>
