                            <div class="document-card">
                                <div class="document-header">
                                    <div class="document-title">üè¢ Harvard Business Review - Amy Edmondson</div>
                                    <span class="edit-badge">20+ Years Psychological Safety Research</span>
                                </div>
                                <div class="document-content">SOURCE: Harvard Business Review | Academic-Practitioner Bridge

AUTHOR CREDENTIALS: Amy Edmondson (Harvard Business School) - Preeminent psychological safety researcher with 20+ years field validation

CORE INSIGHTS:
‚Ä¢ Psychological safety ‚â† comfort or niceness; it enables candor and productive conflict
‚Ä¢ Leaders consistently underestimate their perceived intimidation factor
‚Ä¢ Decision failures typically stem from information withholding, not information absence
‚Ä¢ Fear of appearing ignorant/incompetent/intrusive/negative suppresses voice behavior

3-STEP IMPLEMENTATION FRAMEWORK:
1. SET THE STAGE: Frame work as learning problem; acknowledge uncertainty
2. INVITE PARTICIPATION: Ask questions; create structures for input
3. RESPOND PRODUCTIVELY: Express appreciation; destigmatize failure

VALIDATED INTERVENTIONS:
‚úì Leader vulnerability modeling
‚úì Explicit invitation for dissent
‚úì Positive response to challenge

RELEVANCE: Provides theoretical foundation and practical guidance for addressing root cause (leader behavior creating psychological safety barriers)

CREDIBILITY: High (Academic rigor + extensive practitioner case studies)</div>
