                            <div class="document-card">
                                <div class="document-header">
                                    <div class="document-title">üë®‚Äçüíº Practitioner Interview: Engineering Team Lead</div>
                                    <span class="edit-badge">8 Years Experience | Mid-Size Tech</span>
                                </div>
                                <div class="document-content">SOURCE: Direct practitioner conversation (anonymized)

PRACTITIONER PROFILE:
‚Ä¢ 8 years managing engineering teams in mid-size technology company
‚Ä¢ Responsible for enterprise software product delivery
‚Ä¢ Direct experience implementing psychological safety interventions

OBSERVED PROBLEM PATTERNS:
"Go along to get along" as default team behavior. Junior engineers hesitant to challenge senior engineers due to technical credibility concerns. Status/seniority hierarchies amplify psychological safety barriers. Result: Missed bugs, suboptimal architecture decisions, preventable rework.

EFFECTIVE INTERVENTIONS:
‚úì PRE-MORTEMS: Significantly improved risk identification
‚úì ANONYMOUS IDEA SUBMISSION: Surfaced concerns never voiced in meetings
‚úì SEPARATE GENERATION FROM EVALUATION: Reduced premature criticism

IMPLEMENTATION WARNINGS:
Generic "we value input" messaging fails without structural change. Introducing tools without changing decision-making processes undermines trust. Leader commitment to acting on feedback is critical.

RELEVANCE: Validates psychological safety problems in engineering contexts; confirms pre-mortems and anonymous tools as practical interventions

CREDIBILITY: Moderate (Direct frontline experience; small sample size)</div>
                            </div>

                            <div class="document-card">
                                <div class="document-header">
                                    <div class="document-title">üë®‚Äçüíº Practitioner Interview: Scrum Master</div>
                                    <span class="edit-badge">5 Years Experience | Cloud Services</span>
                                </div>
                                <div class="document-content">SOURCE: Direct practitioner conversation (anonymized)

PRACTITIONER PROFILE:
‚Ä¢ 5 years facilitating agile teams in cloud services firm
‚Ä¢ Observes team dynamics across sprint cycles and retrospectives
‚Ä¢ Experience implementing structured dissent mechanisms

OBSERVED PROBLEM PATTERNS:
Teams fear appearing negative (positivity bias in agile culture). Conflict avoidance in retrospectives ("retrospective theater"). Fear of "not being a team player" label suppresses dissent. Repeated sprint failures from unvoiced concerns.

EFFECTIVE INTERVENTIONS:
‚úì ROTATING DEVIL'S ADVOCATE: Noticeably increased engagement
‚úì ANONYMOUS RETRO SURVEYS: Surfaced real issues
‚úì FORMALIZED DISSENT ROLES: Made challenge role-based, not personality-dependent

IMPLEMENTATION KEYS:
Rotate roles to avoid individual stigma. Must close feedback loop (collecting without action destroys trust). Dissent must be legitimized, not merely tolerated.

RELEVANCE: Directly validates rotating devil's advocate, anonymous tools, and formalization importance

CREDIBILITY: Moderate (Frontline facilitation experience across multiple teams)</div>
                            </div>
                        </div>

                        <!-- PART 3: ORGANIZATIONAL EVIDENCE -->
