                            <!-- BAYESIAN ANALYSIS -->
                            <div class="process-step-card expanded" onclick="toggleStep('bayesian')">
                                BAYESIAN EVIDENCE AGGREGATION
                            </div>
                            
                            <div id="bayesian-content" class="step-content expanded">
                                <div class="document-card">
                                    <div class="document-header">
                                        <div class="document-title">üé≤ Prior Probability Assessment</div>
                                        <span class="edit-badge">Before Evidence Review</span>
                                    </div>
                                    <div class="document-content">HYPOTHESIS: Structured challenge interventions will improve decision quality in engineering teams

PRIOR PROBABILITY (Before Evidence): 60%

RATIONALE FOR 60% PRIOR:
Based on general management knowledge and intuition before systematic evidence review:

‚úì Reasonable assumption that groupthink exists in organizations
‚úì Common sense suggests diverse perspectives improve decisions
‚úì Some awareness of psychological safety research
‚úì Anecdotal evidence from practitioner observations

‚ö† Uncertainty about:
- Magnitude of effect (how much improvement?)
- Specific intervention effectiveness (which mechanisms work best?)
- Implementation feasibility in real contexts
- Generalizability across organizational settings

BASELINE CONFIDENCE: Moderate (60%) - Plausible hypothesis but lacking systematic evidence</div>
                                </div>

                                <div class="document-card">
                                    <div class="document-header">
                                        <div class="document-title">üìä Likelihood Ratios by Evidence Type</div>
                                        <span class="edit-badge">Evidence Strength Assessment</span>
                                    </div>
                                    <div class="document-content">SCIENTIFIC EVIDENCE LIKELIHOOD RATIO: 4.5

Evidence Strength: Very Strong
- Meta-analysis (Frazier et al.): r=0.44, N=26,471
- Longitudinal field study (Detert & Burris): Voice ‚Üí Decision Quality validated
- Top-tier journals with rigorous peer review
- Effect sizes practically significant (19% variance explained)

Increases confidence from 60% ‚Üí 82%

---

PRACTITIONER EVIDENCE LIKELIHOOD RATIO: 3.0

Evidence Strength: Strong
- Google Project Aristotle: 180 teams, 2-year study
- McKinsey: 25-30% decision improvement with structured processes
- HBR/Edmondson: Extensive field validation
- Direct interviews: Frontline confirmation of mechanisms

Increases confidence from 82% ‚Üí 91%

---

ORGANIZATIONAL EVIDENCE LIKELIHOOD RATIO: 2.5

Evidence Strength: Moderate-Strong
- USAFacts: 62% underreporting validates problem scale
- BLS: $22B annual cost, 48% communication-related
- World Bank: 25-40% performance gap
- JMU: 35% fewer failures with structured dissent (KEY VALIDATION)

Increases confidence from 91% ‚Üí 95%

---

STAKEHOLDER EVIDENCE LIKELIHOOD RATIO: 1.5

Evidence Strength: Moderate
- Secondary source analysis (no primary stakeholder engagement)
- Identifies critical implementation factors (middle managers)
- Reveals feasibility considerations
- Moderate influence on overall confidence

Increases confidence from 95% ‚Üí 96%

---

CONVERGENCE BONUS: +1.5 (for independent source agreement)

All four evidence types independently converge on same conclusions:
‚úì Problem exists (X)
‚úì Mechanism validated (M)
‚úì Outcomes measurable (Y)
‚úì Interventions field-tested

Final adjustment: 96% ‚Üí 97%</div>
                                </div>

