                                    </div>
                                    <div class="document-content">QUESTION: Will the psychological safety ‚Üí decision quality relationship and structured challenge interventions generalize to our mid-size engineering team context?

ANSWER: YES, with high confidence (80%)

SUPPORTING EVIDENCE:

‚úÖ POPULATION MATCH (Very High)
- Frazier meta-analysis includes engineering teams
- Google Project Aristotle studied 180 engineering teams
- BLS and JMU data specifically from engineering contexts
- Target population directly represented in evidence base

‚úÖ PROBLEM MATCH (Very High)
- USAFacts: Engineering/technical roles have highest underreporting
- Practitioner interviews confirm groupthink in engineering teams
- Seniority hierarchies and technical credibility concerns validated
- Junior engineers hesitant to challenge seniors (direct observation)

‚úÖ MECHANISM MATCH (High)
- Information sharing mechanism applies across contexts
- Voice behavior ‚Üí decision quality relationship stable
- Psychological safety principles universal
- Engineering culture may amplify (not diminish) mechanisms

‚úÖ INTERVENTION MATCH (Moderate-High)
- Pre-mortems align with engineering risk assessment practices
- Anonymous tools address technical credibility barriers
- Devil's advocate formalized dissent culturally acceptable
- Structured processes fit engineering mindset

‚ö† CONTEXT DIFFERENCES TO CONSIDER:

- Mid-size organization (not Google's resources)
  ‚Üí Adaptation: Use lightweight tools (Google Forms, not custom platforms)

- Distributed/hybrid teams (if applicable)
  ‚Üí Adaptation: Anonymous tools especially valuable remotely

- Existing agile processes
  ‚Üí Adaptation: Integrate into sprint retros and planning

- Resource constraints
  ‚Üí Adaptation: Start with low-cost interventions (pre-mortems, devil's advocate)

GENERALIZABILITY CONCLUSION:
Core findings generalize very well. Implementation must be adapted to mid-size resource constraints and engineering team norms, but fundamental mechanisms remain valid.</div>
