                        <!-- QUESTION 3 -->
                        <div class="process-step-card" onclick="toggleStep('q3')">
                            QUESTION 3: What are the alternative solutions and their trade-offs?
                        </div>
                        
                        <div id="q3-content" class="step-content">
                            <div class="document-card">
                                <div class="document-header">
                                    <div class="document-title">üîÑ Alternative Solutions Analysis</div>
                                    <span class="edit-badge">Comparison of Options</span>
                                </div>
                                <div class="document-content">QUESTION: What other solutions exist besides our proposed 5-part structured challenge framework, and how do they compare?

ALTERNATIVE 1: Status Quo (Do Nothing)
Pros:
‚úì Zero implementation cost
‚úì No organizational disruption
‚úì Familiar processes

Cons:
‚úó $600K annual losses continue
‚úó Groupthink problems persist and worsen
‚úó Competitive disadvantage grows
‚úó Junior talent attrition continues

Expected Value: -$600K annually (ongoing losses)
Probability of Success: 0%

---

ALTERNATIVE 2: Leadership Training Only
Approach: Train managers on psychological safety without structural interventions

Pros:
‚úì Lower cost (~$15K one-time)
‚úì Addresses root cause (leader behavior)
‚úì Quick to implement

Cons:
‚úó No structural support for dissent
‚úó Reliant on individual manager behavior change
‚úó Informal mechanisms easily fade
‚úó Limited evidence of standalone effectiveness

Expected Value: $150K annually (25% of full benefit)
Probability of Success: 40%
Evidence Quality: Moderate (HBR/Edmondson supports, but limited quantitative validation)

---

ALTERNATIVE 3: Anonymous Tools Only
Approach: Deploy Slido/SurveyMonkey for anonymous input, skip other interventions

Pros:
‚úì Very low cost (~$2K annually)
‚úì Quick implementation
‚úì High team member acceptance
‚úì Immediate impact on surfacing concerns

Cons:
‚úó No formalized dissent roles
‚úó Lacks leader behavior change
‚úó May surface issues without decision-making integration
‚úó Risk of "collecting feedback but not acting"

Expected Value: $200K annually (33% of full benefit)
Probability of Success: 50%
Evidence Quality: Moderate (practitioner validation, limited large-scale data)

---

ALTERNATIVE 4: External Consulting Engagement
Approach: Hire McKinsey/Deloitte to design and implement culture change

Pros:
‚úì Expert facilitation and design
‚úì Best-practice frameworks
‚úì Comprehensive support

Cons:
‚úó Very high cost ($150K-$300K engagement)
‚úó External dependency (not sustainable)
‚úó May not be culturally tailored
‚úó ROI heavily dependent on follow-through after consultants leave

Expected Value: $300K annually net (50% benefit, but high costs year 1)
Probability of Success: 60%
Evidence Quality: High (McKinsey data validates approach)

---

PROPOSED SOLUTION: 5-Part Structured Challenge Framework
Approach: Rotating devil's advocate + anonymous tools + pre-mortems + bias training + structured challenge

Pros:
‚úì Evidence-based (all components validated)
‚úì Comprehensive (addresses structure, behavior, culture)
‚úì Moderate cost ($27K year 1, $7K annually)
‚úì Multiple reinforcing mechanisms
‚úì Sustainable (builds internal capability)

Cons:
‚ö† Requires sustained commitment
‚ö† Cultural shift takes time (quarters, not weeks)
‚ö† Middle manager buy-in critical

Expected Value: $573K annually net
Probability of Success: 70%
Evidence Quality: Very High (convergent evidence across all 4 types)

---

COMPARISON SUMMARY:

| Alternative | Cost (Year 1) | Expected Value | Success Prob. | Evidence |
|------------|---------------|----------------|---------------|----------|
| Status Quo | $0 | -$600K | 0% | N/A |
| Training Only | $15K | $150K | 40% | Moderate |
| Anonymous Tools | $2K | $200K | 50% | Moderate |
| Consulting | $200K | $300K | 60% | High |
| **Proposed** | **$27K** | **$573K** | **70%** | **Very High** |

DECISION: Proposed 5-part framework has highest expected value, moderate cost, and strongest evidence base. Combines best elements of alternatives (leader training + anonymous tools) while adding structural mechanisms (devil's advocate, pre-mortems) for sustained impact.</div>
